description: Published by City Magazines, Solo was one of their few late 1960s ventures not tied to City's deal with Century 21 Publications. Instead it focused on other licenses, such as Man from UNCLE (a reprint of the Gold Key title), Sergeant Bilko (presumably reprinting the DC series), the Scarecrow (reprinting the Gold Key comic adaptation of Disney's movie adaptation of the British Scarecrow of Romney Marsh novels), Disney's Uncle Scrooge and Goofy, and others. In issue 16 the title added a Century 21-related strips, The Mysterons, featuring the villains of then-yet to air new show Captain Scarlet. After 31 issues, Solo was merged into TV Tornado.
name: Solo

deck: Licensed annuals following the adventures of the Doctor's foes the Daleks.
description: As early as 1964 the Daleks had spun off from Doctor Who into their own licensed tales with Souvenir Press' The Dalek Book, predating even the Doctor himself shifting from the television to printed matter. Souvenir Press would print two subsequent books, while TV21 would produce the lengthy Dalek Chronicles, during which time the Doctor's own comic strip adventures in TV Comic were necessarily bereft of Daleks because of TV21's license. However, after the TV21 strip ended and Dalek creator Terry Nation tried and failed to sell a TV spin-off series starring the Daleks to a US studio, the Daleks took a break from having their own adventures, and returned to harassing the Doctor in print as well as on TV. In 1975 World Distributors purchased a license to produce Dalek stories, and for the next four years the Daleks again enjoyed adventures unhindered by their meddling Time Lord foe. World Distributors published four annuals before cancelling the run; a few of the stories within were reprints of segments of the Dalek Chronicles, but most were new material.
name: Dalek Annual

description: Published by World Distributors as a tie-in to the Doctor Who spin-off K-9 and Company, featuring K-9 and Sarah Jane Smith investigating various mysteries. Since the K-9 and Company pilot had pitted the Doctor's two friends against a menace with a supernatural cover, the stories in the annual followed suit. As the series did not progress beyond the pilot episode, this proved to be the only annual in the series.
name: K-9 Annual

deck: The first Doctor Who-related comic tie-in, published by Souvenir Press in June 1964.
description:
The first licensed tie-in fiction related to Doctor Who, Souvenir Press' The Dalek Book saw the Daleks beat the Doctor into both prose and comic strip (the Doctor would not appear in a comic until TV Comic #674, released on 14th November 1964, nearly five months after The Dalek Book was published). Two sequel editions were released annually; though their titles differed slightly, they were part of the same series, with storylines and characters carrying across from one release to the next.

The separate licensing of the Doctor and the Daleks, made possible largely because Dalek creator Terry Nation owned their copyright while the BBC owned the Doctor, meant that the Doctor did not appear in these books, though he is mentioned in the first one, and his granddaughter Susan Foreman does appear in the first, while his later travelling companion Sara Kingdom, who was also owned by Terry Nation, made her comic strip debut in the third. Similarly, because of the Daleks being licensed to appear here and in TV21's Dalek Chronicles, the Doctor was initially unable to encounter them either in his weekly TV Comic strip or the World Distributors Doctor Who Annuals; it was only after the Daleks' solo ventures came to an end that they would menace the Time Lord in comics.

After these three books, it would be nearly a decade before the Daleks again ventured out into solo action in an Annual format, when World Distributors bought the license and produced the Dalek Annuals.
name: Dalek Book

description: In 1973 Polystyle published the first Doctor Who Holiday Special, reprinting some of their previously published TV21 Doctor Who strips alongside new material. The Doctor had previously appeared in several TV Comic Holiday Specials, but this was the first time Polystyle had given him a title to himself. The success of the first issue saw a second released a year later, but Polystyle then left it three years before publishing their next (and final) special, the Doctor Who Winter Special 1977. After Marvel UK took over the license in 1979, they began a more regular run of both Summer and Winter Specials.
name: Doctor Who Holiday Special

description: The third Polystyle Doctor Who special, released three years after the last Doctor Who Holiday Special. Like its predecessors it included articles, comic strips and a text story, but unlike the previous issues the comic strips were not strictly speaking new. Instead it used reprints of past stories from TV Action, with artwork modified to replace Jon Pertwee's third Doctor with Tom Baker's fourth. Only the text story was completely new. It would be Polystyle's last Doctor Who Special before losing the license to Marvel UK.
name: Doctor Who Winter Special

deck: Panini annual release, tying in with the Doctor Who TV series.
description: In 2005 Panini Comics, publishers of Doctor Who Magazine, released the Doctor Who Annual 2006 to tie in with the revival of the TV series on the BBC, the first annual since 1986, and the first annual-like product based on Doctor Who since Panini's 1996 Yearbook. Its success prompted the BBC to take the annual back in-house from the next year, but they permitted Panini to still produce a new annual-like product, so long as it did not have the word annual in the title. With the BBC annual aimed at younger readers and heavy on features and games, Panini aimed its publication at a slightly older market, with a product full of prose shorts and comic strips, many scribed by established Doctor Who writers such as the TV show's head writer and producer Russell T. Davies and future head writer/producer Steven Moffat. Four volumes were released from 2006 to 2009, the 2007 to 2010 Storybooks, and a Storybook 2011 was being worked on when BBC apparently withdrew the license. A year later the BBC replaced the Storybooks with their own annual Doctor Who The Brilliant Book.
name: Doctor Who Storybook

deck: A Grandreams annual tying in with a TV adaptation of Sherlock Holmes.
description: When ITV bought the rights to air Sherlock Holmes and Doctor Watson, a Polish/American joint venture based on Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's Sherlock Holmes that starred Geoffrey Whitehead as the eponymous detective and Donald Pickering as Doctor Watson, Grandreams bought a license to produce a TV tie-in annual for the UK market. Unfortunately ITV's plans to air the series, which included adaptations of existing Holmes tales alongside brand new stories, fell through, so the show never aired in the UK, but Grandreams released their annual anyway. Unsurprisingly, no subsequent annuals were forthcoming.

description:
Collects Terminal City #1-9 and Terminal City: Aerial Graffiti #1-5, which were originally serialized in the 90's by Vertigo.

Visionary designer and comics creator Dean Motter (Mister X, Elecropolis, Batman: Nine Lives) returns with the purest expression to date of his patented retro futurism! Terminal City is a place where transistor-tube robots rub elbows with old-time gangsters, where bright, shiny technologies cast deep noir shadows. The city has been in decline since a group of celebrated adventurers - Kid Gloves, the boxer; Monty Vickers, the explorer; Eno Orez, the Man of 1,000 Faces, and Cosmo Quinn, the human fly - were each disgraced or disappeared into obscurity. Now a series of strange mysteries involving an unopenable briefcase, a missing link in evolution, a daring lady in red, and an obscene skywriter brings the four men together once again, some on the side of the law, some involved in shady business, with explosive results!
name: Compleat Terminal City
